amdgpu: gmc_v7_0 — bump Liverpool/Gladius GART size to 16 GB (v76d-β-1)

v76d-α proved that range-protection isn't the gate. With the LVP/GL vmid
1..15 END_ADDR widened to 32 GB, the UVD firmware's hardcoded GPU virtual
0x300000000 access still hits the same fault as v76b. That means the
fault is a real "no PTE present" miss on the PT walk, not a range trip.

The PS4 GART is 512 MB by default (drivers/gpu/drm/amd/amdgpu/gmc_v7_0.c
line 408). That covers GPU virtual 0..0x1FFFFFFF only. The firmware
reads at 0x300000000 (= 12 GB) which is way past the PT, so GMC has no
entry to look up and raises VM_L2_PROTECTION_FAULT.

Sony's UVD VCPU register writes (Ghidra'd in uvd_vcpu_start_baikal,
FUN_c88f8610) show the cache regions stay under 1.4 MB total
(mmUVD_VCPU_CACHE_OFFSET0..2). So the 0x300000000 access is NOT a cache
read — it's some other VCPU buffer (stack, save/restore, DMA descriptor
queue). Sony's gbase_map evidently has a real PTE there in vmid 4; we
don't.

This patch widens the Liverpool/Gladius GART from 512 MB to 16 GB so
the shared PT (mainline amdgpu makes all VMIDs share the GART) spans
0x300000000. Missing PTEs at that index will fall through to
mmVM_CONTEXT*_PROTECTION_FAULT_DEFAULT_ADDR (adev->dummy_page_addr) —
the standard "unmapped GART read" path that returns zeros to the
requester instead of generating a fault.

  case CHIP_LIVERPOOL:
  case CHIP_GLADIUS:
-     adev->gmc.gart_size = 512ULL << 20;     /* 512 MB */
+     adev->gmc.gart_size = 16ULL << 30;      /* 16 GB */
      break;

Cost: 4M PTEs × 8 bytes = 32 MB of GTT memory for the page table. On
PS4's 8 GB unified that's 0.4% — comfortable. PT is sparse-populated
by amdgpu_gart_init, so most of those 32 MB stay zero.

Expected hardware signals:

  ✅ "no STATUS bit 1 after 2s" disappears, VCPU starts. The
     dummy_page_addr fallback is enough; firmware tolerates zero reads
     at 0x300000000. Subsequent failure (if any) tells us what comes
     next in the bring-up.

  🟡 Fault changes form: a different vmid, different address, or a
     different fault code. The firmware made progress past the
     0x300000000 read but tripped on the next thing it needs.

  ❌ Same vmid 4 page 3145728 fault, same VCPU timeout. Then either:
     - the GART expansion didn't take effect (build/apply issue —
       verify via "amdgpu: GART: 16384M" in dmesg)
     - the firmware does an explicit walk that requires a real (non-zero)
       PTE at 0x300000000. v76d-β-2: bind a small BO at that GPU VA
       so the PT entry resolves to real memory.

  💀 Boot regression in GFX, SDMA, or DCE. amdgpu_gart_init/_bind may
     have hidden assumptions about size. If this happens, revert and
     pivot to v76d-β-3 (per-vmid custom PD) — bigger change but
     scoped to UVD's VMID.

Built and md5-verified before submitting for hardware test.

Signed-off-by: Meerzulee <mirzaali@screeninternational.org>

--- a/drivers/gpu/drm/amd/amdgpu/gmc_v7_0.c
+++ b/drivers/gpu/drm/amd/amdgpu/gmc_v7_0.c
@@ -405,7 +405,24 @@
 #ifdef CONFIG_DRM_AMDGPU_CIK
 		case CHIP_LIVERPOOL:
 		case CHIP_GLADIUS:
-			adev->gmc.gart_size = 512ULL << 20;
+			/*
+			 * v76d-β-1: bump GART from 512 MB to 16 GB.
+			 *
+			 * Sony's UVD VCPU firmware accesses GPU virtual
+			 * 0x300000000 (12 GB) once started — neither cache
+			 * (covered by mmUVD_VCPU_CACHE_OFFSET*) nor VRAM
+			 * (0xF00000000+). v76d-α proved this is a real
+			 * no-PTE miss on the shared GART, not a range
+			 * trip. By extending GART to span 16 GB the
+			 * firmware's VA falls inside the PT, missing
+			 * entries fall through to dummy_page_addr instead
+			 * of faulting, and the VCPU at least gets PAST
+			 * the protection-fault stall.
+			 *
+			 * Cost: 4M PTEs * 8 bytes = 32 MB of GTT memory
+			 * for the page table. PS4 has 8 GB unified, so 0.4%.
+			 */
+			adev->gmc.gart_size = 16ULL << 30;
 			break;
 		case CHIP_BONAIRE: /* UVD, VCE do not support GPUVM */
 		case CHIP_HAWAII:  /* UVD, VCE do not support GPUVM */
